metadata.name: Refractions #248
metadata.description:
Refractions is a study of frequencies, harmonies and abstract representations of natural phenomena. 

It is an experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.


Probabilities;

- 14 compositions with variations.

- 2 background color.

- 19 different base color palette (2 monochrome).

- 2 distinct textures with variations.

-  2 different alpha types; tangential & sinusoidal.

- Different edges.

- Several starting positions and styles (wavy or straight).


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, April 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Welcome #31
metadata.description: This long-form generative token creates the scene across 500 frames (iterations) of the system.  It takes about 40-45 seconds to generate the preview, so please be patient.  Once generated, collectors can watch their scene emerge from start to finish.  Press DOWN to save any frame.  The system uses angular flow fields, sinusoidal waves, stochastic randomness, gradient algorithms and color procedures to produce a wide range of variety.

metadata.name: Anachronous #65
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Balanced #69
metadata.description:
What does balance look like when viewed through the lens of pure mathematics? This is the question Balanced attempts to answer.

Each output is composed of a unique collection of blocks mathematically stacked to be in perfect balance.

This is my Genesis project. Enjoy!

Interactions:
1 - Reverse your stack vertically and re-balance.
2 - Toggle between square and portrait frame.
3 - Show center of mass. 
4 - Toggle the border.
5 - Toggle the background (color/transparent)
6 - Export image (2048x2048)
7 - Export image (4096x4096)
8 - Export image (8192x8192)

How it was made: https://www.jeffweber.art/balanced

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #156
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It’s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you’re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic “Hashed/Hatched” aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: The Light of Summer #58
metadata.description:
Description of Seasons of Siskiyou Series
Surrounding my home, covering more than one million acres, is the Rogue River - Siskiyou National Forest which takes up three southern Oregon counties and one northern California county. It’s a magical place that fills the imagination and lifts the spirit; a place that inspires with its uniqueness, its legends, and its larger-than-life vistas.

Each season in the Siskiyou mountains is a unique experience unto itself. So, with an attention to the feelings this place evokes at any given time of the year, I designed four generative tokens to create an impression of the emotion–the calming quietness; the peaceful solitude; the overwhelming contrasts and variety of forms, shapes and textures; the magic and playful mystery; the welcomingness and foreboding. These four works feature clever and inventive creative coding techniques in a rich, graphic style to craft a stunning impression of the Seasons of Siskiyou.


Token 2 of 4 - THE LIGHT OF SUMMER (1990 x 1080) p5js Generative Token.
After weeks of a lengthening day, the color of spring gives way to the light of summer.  The air glows with the warmth of an apex sun; the coolness of the shadows welcomes tiny denizens; golden hues of drying flora frame the brilliance of lingering blooms.  Magic sails in solar breezes lazily drifting along with the whims of daylight.  Hike along remote trails, lose yourself in the unique beauty, and be immersed in the Light of Summer.

Output and Coding Features of “The Light of Summer”:

The Light of Summer features a variety of recursive algorithms to generate a range of plant forms.  The flowers are created with skewable vectored-ellipses to provide depth.  The output is generated by layering various generative systems using a one-point perspective.  An optical effect is applied to create atmosphere and accent-textures.  A radial gradient sets the background and frames the scene with a sense of atmosphere and humidity. 

Press DOWN ARROW to save the output as a png image file.

Each iteration varies the color palette, shape and density of the vegetation, the position and density of flowers and the optical-effect texture.

Token Published April 21, 2022 on FXHASH set at 75 Editions.
Written and designed by Ed Cavett using the p5js library.
Token 2 of 4 from the series “The Seasons of Siskiyou.”
